And it's just very encouraging.

00:24:34.102 --> 00:24:36.293
So while it is a weird kind of 
thing, it does create certain 

00:24:36.294 --> 00:24:38.294
communities, and 

00:24:41.365 --> 00:24:44.861
it does help bring like-minded 
people together to make points. 

00:24:44.862 --> 00:24:47.699
Even if we're just patting each 
other on our backs, you know, it

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:51.435
kind of feels good.  It's a 
community.

00:24:55.935 --> 00:24:57.559
&gt;&gt;  Well, I was going to say 
that most illustrators -- I 

00:24:57.560 --> 00:25:02.310
can't speak for cartoonists, but
I imagine it's very similar, we 

00:25:02.311 --> 00:25:07.222
work by ourselves.  So unless 
you're going out and teaching 

00:25:07.223 --> 00:25:09.278
and getting yourself exposed to 
people in a work situations, the

00:25:09.279 --> 00:25:14.599
mar jort of your time you spend 
by yourself, and so social media

00:25:14.600 --> 00:25:16.600
adds a layer of connectivity 
that is really helpful.

00:25:19.632 --> 00:25:21.591
You get to see what other people
are doing or tell them what you 

00:25:21.592 --> 00:25:23.592
think about what they're doing.

00:25:25.899 --> 00:25:27.899
The other side of it, too, is 
that there 

00:25:29.974 --> 00:25:31.974
have been quite a few places 
where women 

00:25:33.661 --> 00:25:35.661
have gotten beaten up in social 
media, 

00:25:36.910 --> 00:25:39.151
and other places where they can 
find refuge.  There are some 

00:25:39.152 --> 00:25:41.202
private Facebook groups where 
people can -- women can talk 

00:25:41.203 --> 00:25:45.469
about what is happening with 
them.  They can talk about 

00:25:45.470 --> 00:25:47.470
whether they think 

00:25:48.528 --> 00:25:50.972
they're getting paid less or 
whether somebody is bullying 

00:25:50.973 --> 00:25:55.464
them or other, you know, topics 
that are distressful and you 

00:25:55.465 --> 00:25:57.944
need to find support somewhere.

00:26:03.261 --> 00:26:05.261
So it's like everything, it's 
got otwo sides.

00:26:06.099 --> 00:26:07.744
&gt;&gt;  I think that social media 
has brought a lot of different 

00:26:07.745 --> 00:26:09.798
kinds of people to illustration 
and comics, and 

00:26:13.297 --> 00:26:15.297
it was very, very much needed, 
because 

00:26:16.596 --> 00:26:19.089
it is -- I feel like when I 
started, very predominantly 

00:26:19.090 --> 00:26:21.298
white male and straight and, 
like, now I feel like it's 

00:26:21.512 --> 00:26:23.512
really expanded.

00:26:25.177 --> 00:26:26.861
And I used to -- when I started,
I really linked illustration 

00:26:26.862 --> 00:26:29.911
with this commercial aspect.  
It's like, you're not an artist,

00:26:32.139 --> 00:26:34.193
you're working with a client, 
you know what I mean?  And 

00:26:34.194 --> 00:26:36.194
you're creating a product.

00:26:39.477 --> 00:26:41.720
And now I feel like I can't -- I
feel it's a much more nebulous 

00:26:41.721 --> 00:26:45.195
thing that actually because it's
brought in all these different 

00:26:45.196 --> 00:26:47.196
people, really question some of 
the power structures around it 

00:26:49.094 --> 00:26:51.106
and, like, how it moves and 
they're not necessarily -- they 

00:26:51.107 --> 00:26:53.107
think about it in a 

00:26:54.122 --> 00:26:56.762
really, really different way, 
and it's -- but it can be really

00:26:56.763 --> 00:26:58.763
scary, some of 

00:27:01.490 --> 00:27:03.329
this stuff with the being a 
woman on the Internet is like 

00:27:03.330 --> 00:27:06.170
just kind of a scary place 
sometimes.  But I can't imagine 

00:27:06.171 --> 00:27:09.017
my career without it.  I 
graduated in 2003, like right at

00:27:09.018 --> 00:27:11.274
the start of it, and I just 
don't think I 

00:27:14.534 --> 00:27:16.534
would be where I am without 
continually 

00:27:17.795 --> 00:27:19.795
sharing online and you're never 
supposed 

00:27:21.242 --> 00:27:23.099
to say that audience reaction, 
or whatever, but I feel totally 

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:27.799
-- because I know a lot of my 
audience is women, that's where 

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:30.235
you can connect, especially with
young women, teenagers, right?  

00:27:30.236 --> 00:27:32.236
That's where they are.

00:27:33.895 --> 00:27:35.964
So I found it like a very -- I 
can't separate the two.  I 

00:27:35.965 --> 00:27:38.201
wouldn't want to either.  
There's the good and the bad.

00:27:38.801 --> 00:27:44.129
&gt;&gt;  There's a little bit of a 
democracy, too, in someone can 

00:27:44.130 --> 00:27:48.599
have connection to the Internet 
and look at things on social 

00:27:48.600 --> 00:27:50.600
media and not have to have the 
money to buy a book.

00:27:52.706 --> 00:27:54.131
So they might like Jillian's 
work or Barbara's work and they 

00:27:54.132 --> 00:27:58.034
might not be able to afford that
book or get that book, but they 

00:27:58.035 --> 00:28:00.035
can appreciate their work 

00:28:01.493 --> 00:28:03.493
through social media that 
they're on anyway.

00:28:03.961 --> 00:28:06.622
&gt;&gt;  And we haven't figured out 
how to get paid either.  Like 

00:28:06.623 --> 00:28:08.257
you don't know how to make money
from --

00:28:08.258 --> 00:28:09.273
&gt;&gt;  I hear ya.
&gt;&gt;  Putting your stuff out 

00:28:09.274 --> 00:28:13.390
there.  It's not a clear road.
&gt;&gt;  And illustration, because of

00:28:13.391 --> 00:28:15.391
this, 

00:28:16.573 --> 00:28:17.995
it has become so incredibly 
popular.  Like when I started, I

00:28:17.996 --> 00:28:19.996
feel like it 

00:28:21.591 --> 00:28:23.591
was for nerds that wanted to 
like air 

00:28:24.682 --> 00:28:26.682
brush like shiny metal and 
stuff, but 

00:28:30.111 --> 00:28:31.269
it's like completely, like, 
evolved to this other -- I can't

00:28:31.270 --> 00:28:33.593
remember what I was going to 
say, but...

00:28:34.406 --> 00:28:37.323
[chuckles]
I got distracted talking about 

00:28:37.324 --> 00:28:40.600
nerds for a second.
&gt;&gt;  Not getting paid.

00:28:41.608 --> 00:28:44.811
&gt;&gt;  About not getting paid.
&gt;&gt;  Thank you from the audience,

00:28:44.812 --> 00:28:48.461
not getting paid.
That you end up -- there's like 

00:28:48.462 --> 00:28:53.156
an economy of, like, "likes" and
stuff like that and I think that

00:28:53.157 --> 00:28:56.215
-- one thing I heard about this 
is sort of directly to women on 

00:28:56.216 --> 00:29:01.133
the Internet. I kind of feel 
like sometimes you need to 

00:29:01.134 --> 00:29:02.359
present an image, and that 
really values the young woman, 

00:29:02.360 --> 00:29:04.360
the woman that 

00:29:05.648 --> 00:29:07.648
is willing to sort of put her 
appearance online.

00:29:09.312 --> 00:29:11.762
And I'm always very -- when I 
was sorting out, I really felt 

00:29:11.763 --> 00:29:16.303
like I tried very hard to keep 
all my images -- like all images

00:29:16.304 --> 00:29:18.972
of myself off the Internet, 
because I didn't want my image 

00:29:18.973 --> 00:29:22.595
linked to my work.  I wanted my 
work to just stand on its own, 

00:29:22.596 --> 00:29:24.596
and stuff like that.

00:29:26.506 --> 00:29:27.939
And I have heard that recently 
some young women feel that's not

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:29.940
a possibility.

00:29:31.411 --> 00:29:33.639
You need an attached image to 
it, an attached persona and 

00:29:33.640 --> 00:29:35.640
personality and, like, brand.

00:29:37.503 --> 00:29:39.503
And I feel like is really 
complicated.

00:29:40.459 --> 00:29:42.460
&gt;&gt;  That's fascinating.
&gt;&gt;  Thank you.

00:29:44.719 --> 00:29:46.719
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;  All right.

00:29:52.544 --> 00:29:55.437
Turning to a slightly different 
but related topic, could you 

00:29:55.438 --> 00:29:57.438
share 

00:29:58.693 --> 00:30:00.693
observations or insights about 
women in 

00:30:01.706 --> 00:30:03.706
these

00:30:05.467 --> 00:30:07.467
fields from your experiences as 

00:30:10.842 --> 00:30:12.058
teachers or being on panels or 
have you benefited from 

00:30:12.059 --> 00:30:14.059
teaching?

00:30:15.949 --> 00:30:17.949
And doing...
[chuckles]

00:30:20.262 --> 00:30:22.262
I know two of you have taught, I
know that.

00:30:23.174 --> 00:30:25.812
&gt;&gt;  I have been teaching for a 
long time and when I first 

00:30:25.813 --> 00:30:27.813
started -- well, I'll go back 
just a little bit more and give 

00:30:28.461 --> 00:30:30.719
you a little bit of a story.  
When I graduated college, 

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:33.571
somebody said to me, oh, do you 
think, you know, you want to 

00:30:33.572 --> 00:30:36.819
teach?  And I said, there's no 
way I want to teach.  Why would 

00:30:36.820 --> 00:30:38.820
I want to teach?  I want to do 
stuff.

00:30:45.107 --> 00:30:46.123
And I think at that time, too, 
it was... you wanted to get out 

00:30:46.124 --> 00:30:49.526
there.  You wanted to build your
portfolio, you wanted to get 

00:30:49.527 --> 00:30:53.402
more clients.  That's what you 
wanted to do if you wanted to be

00:30:53.403 --> 00:30:55.403
an illustrator, so that's what I
wanted to do too.

00:30:58.512 --> 00:31:00.530
But over time, what I found was 
that it gets a little lonely 

00:31:00.531 --> 00:31:04.227
sometimes, so you have to find 
diversion, get away from the 

00:31:04.228 --> 00:31:06.707
four walls that you're in, and I
think a lot of women do have 

00:31:06.708 --> 00:31:09.155
studios in their homes for 
whatever reason.

00:31:14.238 --> 00:31:16.707
I did because I was a parent and
I had a small child and I wanted

00:31:16.708 --> 00:31:20.996
to be able to do that and do my 
work.  But I also wanted to kind

00:31:20.997 --> 00:31:22.997
of connect 

00:31:25.285 --> 00:31:27.285
out with other people, and so 
someone I 

00:31:28.361 --> 00:31:29.991
knew asked me to do a workshop 
on putting -- and this is when I

00:31:29.992 --> 00:31:32.873
was actually doing graphic 
design as well.

00:31:38.596 --> 00:31:41.057
To show how to make 
comprehensive -- these are put 

00:31:41.058 --> 00:31:46.601
together -- this is pre-digital 
world, for anybody that is under

00:31:46.602 --> 00:31:48.230
30, pre-digital world, where if 
you were going to do a design, 

00:31:48.231 --> 00:31:52.325
you put it together, you mocked 
it up to show your client what 

00:31:52.326 --> 00:31:54.761
it was going to look like, and 
so I did this workshop and I 

00:31:57.671 --> 00:32:00.113
was, like, really charged up 
over this idea that I had stuff 

00:32:00.114 --> 00:32:04.790
that I had done and I could put 
that together in an organized 

00:32:04.791 --> 00:32:07.262
way and I could transmit it to a
bunch of students that were 

00:32:07.263 --> 00:32:09.263
eager to 

00:32:10.327 --> 00:32:13.192
get that information, and it 
made me feel like I had this 

00:32:13.193 --> 00:32:16.273
other value beyond what I was 
generating.  So I'm building my 

00:32:16.274 --> 00:32:18.274
career, right?

00:32:19.742 --> 00:32:21.989
But I'm also able to push back 
some things, push back some 

00:32:21.990 --> 00:32:26.917
value to others.  And so that 
kind of got me hooked on doing 

00:32:26.918 --> 00:32:28.918
it, and then over the years I 
was 

00:32:30.803 --> 00:32:32.809
picking up part-time work just 
as a dimension to my studio 

00:32:32.810 --> 00:32:34.810
work.

00:32:41.242 --> 00:32:43.242
And then in 2000 I was recruited
to 

00:32:48.648 --> 00:32:50.648
lead the undergraduate at MICA 
in illustration.

00:32:51.978 --> 00:32:53.978
I had a really vital studio 
business.

00:32:55.445 --> 00:32:57.893
It was something that I really 
had to think long and hard 

00:32:57.894 --> 00:32:59.894
about, but I felt like there 
were some -- it was a challenge.

00:33:01.564 --> 00:33:03.564
It was a good challenge for me.

00:33:05.240 --> 00:33:08.102
So I did that for 10 years and 
started a master's program and 

00:33:08.103 --> 00:33:10.103
we're in year eight.  I think 
it's successful.

00:33:12.822 --> 00:33:14.822
So what do I get out of teaching
is I 

00:33:16.277 --> 00:33:18.277
get to get out of my house and 
my studio.

00:33:19.741 --> 00:33:22.590
But beyond that, it's the same 
exchange.  It's that same 

00:33:22.591 --> 00:33:24.591
bringing value to other people's
lives, sharing things that I do 

00:33:28.770 --> 00:33:30.994
and that I love that are 
meaningful to me, and to raise 

00:33:30.995 --> 00:33:32.995
up people that are interested in
learning.

00:33:34.860 --> 00:33:37.522
I think there's nothing better 
than this relationship of you 

00:33:37.523 --> 00:33:40.801
giving something to someone 
else, them valuing it, and then 

00:33:40.802 --> 00:33:43.653
doing something with that.  And 
that to me, that's what teaching

00:33:43.654 --> 00:33:45.654
is.

00:33:47.310 --> 00:33:50.160
&gt;&gt;  You can see what's cool...
[ Laughter ]

00:33:52.208 --> 00:33:54.208
&gt;&gt;  I don't teach right now, but
I 

00:33:55.258 --> 00:33:57.069
taught for a long time in New 
York and you would see stuff 

00:33:57.070 --> 00:33:59.731
percolating in them and then it 
