00:34:02.073 --> 00:34:03.495
culture, like, two years later 
or something like that, because 

00:34:03.496 --> 00:34:05.496
they're cool art students.

00:34:10.317 --> 00:34:12.317
But, yeah, I don't teach now, 
all the same.

00:34:13.451 --> 00:34:15.451
I mean, it's incredibly 
gratifying to 

00:34:16.709 --> 00:34:18.152
see them grow as people, such a 
formative time, they're like 

00:34:18.153 --> 00:34:22.037
little babies when they start 
and by the end they're like 

00:34:22.038 --> 00:34:24.071
adults and it's really a 
privilege to help somebody on 

00:34:24.072 --> 00:34:26.072
that.

00:34:28.635 --> 00:34:31.106
I did feel like in the end it 
can get tricky because it's -- 

00:34:31.107 --> 00:34:33.107
especially New 

00:34:34.108 --> 00:34:37.093
York art schools are very 
expensive and then this realm of

00:34:37.094 --> 00:34:38.688
student loans and it becomes 
this very incredibly rarefied 

00:34:38.689 --> 00:34:40.689
experience.

00:34:44.024 --> 00:34:45.895
So that -- we haven't talked 
about intersectionality a lot in

00:34:45.896 --> 00:34:48.135
this discussion, but that 
becomes a lot of it 

00:34:51.182 --> 00:34:53.182
too, with accessibility, and 
that was, like...

00:34:54.688 --> 00:34:57.350
that's a changing thing that -- 
